  "What is 'Ohm's law'?": "",
  "The law of conservation of charge": "",
  "The law relating force and acceleration": "",
  "The relationship V = IR, stating that voltage equals current times resistance": "",
  "The law governing capacitor charging": "",
  "Ohm's law: V = IR states that the voltage across an ohmic conductor is proportional to the current through it. R is the constant of proportionality (resistance).": "",
  "What does 'electromotive force' (EMF) mean?": "",
  "A mechanical force applied to a circuit": "",
  "The current produced by a generator": "",
  "The resistance of a battery": "",
  "The voltage provided by a source such as a battery that drives current through a circuit": "",
  "EMF (ε) is the energy per unit charge supplied by a source (battery, generator). Despite the name, it is not a force but a voltage (measured in volts) that drives charge through the circuit.": "",
  "What is 'Kirchhoff's junction rule'?": "",
  "Resistance increases at junctions": "",
  "The sum of voltages around a loop equals zero": "",
  "The sum of currents entering a junction equals the sum of currents leaving it": "",
  "Power is conserved at junctions": "",
  "Kirchhoff's junction (current) rule is based on conservation of charge: the total current entering a node must equal the total current leaving it.": "",
  "What is 'Kirchhoff's loop rule'?": "",
  "The sum of all potential differences (voltage gains and drops) around any closed loop in a circuit equals zero": "",
  "Current flows in loops only when a switch is closed": "",
  "Resistance in a loop is always the same": "",
  "The total current in a loop is constant": "",
  "Kirchhoff's loop (voltage) rule is based on conservation of energy: the sum of EMFs and voltage drops around any closed loop is zero.": "",
  "What does 'internal resistance' of a battery mean?": "",
  "The resistance that prevents the battery from overcharging": "",
  "The inherent resistance within the battery itself that causes a voltage drop when current flows": "",
  "The insulation resistance of the battery casing": "",
  "The resistance of the external circuit connected to the battery": "",
  "Internal resistance (r) is the resistance within the battery due to its materials. The terminal voltage is V = ε − Ir, which is less than the EMF when current flows.": "",
  "What does 'resistivity' refer to?": "",
  "The total resistance of a circuit": "",
  "The power consumed per unit length of wire": "",
  "The ratio of current to voltage": "",
  "An intrinsic property of a material that quantifies how strongly it resists current flow": "",
  "Resistivity (ρ) is a material property measured in Ω·m. A wire's resistance depends on resistivity, length, and cross-sectional area: R = ρL/A.": "",
  "What is 'electric power'?": "",
  "The maximum voltage in a circuit": "",
  "The rate at which electrical energy is converted to other forms: P = IV": "",
  "The total charge stored in a circuit": "",
  "The resistance times the current": "",
  "Electric power P = IV = I²R = V²/R is the rate of energy transfer or conversion in a circuit. It is measured in watts (W).": "",
  "What does 'short circuit' mean?": "",
  "A circuit that is physically short in length": "",
  "A low-resistance path that allows excessive current to flow, bypassing the intended circuit": "",
  "A circuit that has been turned off": "",
  "A circuit with very high resistance": "",
  "A short circuit is an unintended low-resistance path that diverts most of the current. It causes very high current flow, which can overheat wires and cause fires. Fuses and circuit breakers protect against this.": "",
  "What is a 'voltmeter' and how is it connected?": "",
  "A device that measures power; connected at the source": "",
  "A device that measures voltage (potential difference); connected in parallel across the component": "",
  "A device that measures current; connected in series": "",
  "A device that measures resistance; connected in series": "",
  "A voltmeter measures the potential difference across a component and must be connected in parallel. It has very high internal resistance so it draws negligible current.": "",
  "What is an 'ammeter' and how is it connected?": "",
  "A device that measures resistance; connected in parallel": "",
  "A device that measures voltage; connected in parallel": "",
  "A device that measures charge; connected at the battery": "",
  "An ammeter measures the current flowing through a component and must be connected in series. It has very low internal resistance so it does not significantly affect the circuit.": "",
  "A household circuit breaker is rated at 15 A on a 120 V line. What is the maximum power that can be drawn from this circuit before the breaker trips?": "",
  "1,800 W": "",
  "180 W": "",
  "8 W": "",
  "1,500 W": "",
